     2| * IVX Developer Execution Output Guard
     3| *
     4| * Final safety net for the self-developer route. The router already sends
     5| * development commands to the senior-developer runtime, and
     6| * `buildSeniorDeveloperExecutionAnswer` already renders the strict evidence
     7| * format. This module is the LAST line of defence: it inspects the answer that
     8| * is about to be returned to the owner and BLOCKS it when it is narrative-only
     9| * or makes a claim it has not proven.
    10| *
    11| * Hard rules enforced here (owner spec):
    12| *   - No narrative-only answers. The strict section headers must be present.
    13| *   - No "reviewed/prepared/initialized/awaiting approval/development phase/
    14| *     schema planning" prose unless real proof (raw command output) is present.
    15| *   - No "verified" claim without raw command output (`$ ... exit code:`).
    16| *   - No "deployed" claim without a live endpoint / commit proof line.
    17| *   - No "done/complete" claim without a real file diff.
    18| *
    19| * Pure and deterministic (no network / filesystem / AI) so it is fully unit
    20| * testable.
    21| */
    22|
    23|/**
    24| * Sentinel embedded in a guard-blocked answer. When present (together with a
    25| * BLOCKED status and NO CODE CHANGED), the answer is a recognised compliant
    26| * terminal state: it makes no success claims, so validation must not re-trigger
    27| * on the violation reasons it quotes (which legitimately mention words like
    28| * "verified"/"deployed"). This keeps the guard idempotent.
    29| */
    30|export const DEVELOPER_EXECUTION_GUARD_MARKER = 'failed developer-execution enforcement';
